From: indigoidk <indigoidk@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Sat, 18 Jul 2026 12:35:54 -0500
Subject: [PATCH 10/13] hp98644: fix the card ID (native 0x42) and drop the
 fake loopback shadow

Two HP 98644A register-accuracy fixes:

1. The DIO card ID is primary ID 2 (bits 4:0) plus a secondary ID in
   bits 6:5. The native 98644A reports secondary ID 2 -> 0x42; its
   98626-compatibility mode reports secondary ID 0 -> 0x02. The model had
   this backwards (0x02 native, |0x40 for 98626 emulation) and defaulted
   to the emulation value, so the Series 300 boot ROM identifies the card
   as "HP98626" instead of "HP98644". Return 0x42 natively / 0x02 in
   emulation mode. Verified against the Rev C boot ROM ID table
   (0x42="HP98644", 0x02="HP98626") and the 98644A reference manual. With
   the Remote bit these become 0xC2/0x82; OpenBSD's dca accepts all of
   0x02/0x42/0x82/0xC2, so both the serial console and the Remote-DIP
   kernel console keep working.

2. The board kept a private one-byte loopback shadow (m_loopback/m_data)
   that intercepted the data register when MCR LOOP was set, bypassing
   the INS8250's own diagnostic loopback (no LSR THRE/DR, no IIR, no baud
   delay). The real card has no such register -- loopback is the 8250's
   native MCR bit 4. Remove the shadow and let the INS8250 model handle
   loopback.

Validated: hp9k360 / OpenBSD 2.2 boots to a serial login (dca0 attaches
at ID 0x42) and the Remote-DIP kernel console still works (ID 0xC2 =
CN_REMOTE, kernel dmesg reaches the socket).

